Not all fish markets can adapt to sustainable fishing easily, even those following the MSC guidelines have trouble. Governments are also having difficulty on declaring official fishing regulations which is causing the fishing of certain species to be halted like Atlantic Mackerel

How do sustainable fisheries cope with climate change? The Marine Stewardship Council or MSC set out guidelines to help sustainable fisheries. Sustainable fisheries must meet 3 principles: Must keep fish stocks sustainable, low environmental impact, and effective management. https://t.co/LgWms30nhh

Although that climate change is impacting fishing negatively like in areas of the tropics where there is expected to be a decline of up to 40% in wild fish by 2050. Fisheries in higher latitudes are seeing increased ranges in some species. https://t.co/SjPFJbqn0t

So in thinking about options to decrease and/or adapt to climate change, we ought to be thinking explicitly about who benefits and loses from these changes because that is ultimately what we care about, more so than maintaining a stable climate system.
Climate change is in turn a driver of vulnerability.
Of course, vulnerability doesn't fall from the sky: It is itself the product of onrunning social, economic, and ecological processes https://t.co/QakuyoZKCL
So our goal ought to be to focus on how we can reduce people's vulnerability to climate change.
What we're really worried about is that certain people & ecosystems are vulnerable to that rapid change, and will be damaged by it in ways that are morally concerning.

I'm back. I think its helpful to focus on why we care about climate change. Its not that there is anything morally correct about the climate of 1850. Its that rapid change causes problems for people and ecosystems who are adapted to the present.
